ACTIVITY 1: Clustering Cancerous Tissue Samples

1) Read Data

data <- read.arff('golub-1999-v1_database.arff') #  load data

2) Separate Data

Classe <- select(data, Classe) #  separating classes variable from set
sep_data <- data[,-1869]

3) Compute Matrix

DistMatrix <- dist(sep_data[1:1868]) #  calculate distance matrix

4) Single Linkage

SL_points <- hclust(DistMatrix, method = "single") #  cluster with single linkage
plot(SL_points, main = "Single Linkage", xlab = "", sub = "", hang = -1, labels = FALSE) #  plot without labels

5) Complete Linkage

CL_points <- hclust(DistMatrix, method = "complete") #  cluster with complete linkage
plot(CL_points, main = "Complete Linkage", xlab = "", sub = "", hang = -1, labels = FALSE) #  plot without labels

6) Average Linkage

AL_points <- hclust(DistMatrix, method = "average") #  cluster with average linkage 
plot(AL_points, main = "Average Linkage", xlab = "", sub ="", hang = -1, labels = FALSE) #  plot without labels

7) Ward’s

Ward_points <- hclust(DistMatrix, method = "ward.D2") #  cluster with Ward's
plot(Ward_points, main = "Ward's", xlab = "", sub = "", hang = -1, labels = FALSE) #  plot without labels

8) Dendrogram Comparison

When comparing the dendrograms plotted in items 4 to 7. Some clustering algorithms generate more clear clusters than others.

The algorithms that generated the clearer clusters in this case are Ward’s followed by the Complete Linkage Algorithm.

Unlike the other algorithms, Single Linkage may be experiencing a bridging effect that the others would be less susceptible to, while Average Linkage does not seem to show as much of a clear separation either.

9) Class Labels 4 to 7 dendrograms

We will notice that some prominent clusters in the dendrograms below correspond approximately to the classes.

The two sub types of Leukemia are grouped more clearly for Ward’s, Complete, and Average Linkage. The Single Linkage algorithm seems to be able to identify some arbitrarily shaped clusters, however, visually we can see that Single Linkage has a more scattered grouping of the two sub-types of Leukemia, and more outliers within the groups.

This reiterates the notion that the algorithm is more susceptible to noise than the others, and supports the reason as to why there is somewhat of a bridging effect that occurs.

10) Normalized Data

After normalizing the data, we observe very little improvement in the case of Single Linkage. Since normalizing the data should prevent variables with higher value ranges from dominating distance computations, we do see less of a bridging affect in Single Linkage, however there is no improvement in the grouping of the Leukemia sub-types.

When comparing Complete Linkage, once the data has been normalized, we see more of a bridging affect, and a dis improvement in the grouping of the Leukemia sub-types. Since Complete Linkage favors volumetric, globular clusters, by normalizing the data, we see a distortion in the clustering for Complete Linkage.

This could be attributed to the fact that by normalizing the data, the natural differences in variance have been removed, which in turn limits the algorithm in it’s ability categorize variables with wider value ranges as clusters.

We observe a similar case for the Average Linkage algorithm, where there is a distortion in the clustering, and dis improvement in the grouping of the Leukemia sub-types. Ward’s also experiences a similar effect since there is a major dis improvement in the grouping of the sub-types.

Overall, for the purposes of this investigation, it would be more appropriate to make use of Ward’s algorithm with out normalizing the data first.

ACTIVITY 2: Clustering Genes (PART A)

11) Read Data

data <- read.arff('yeast.arff') # read data from ARFF

12) Separate Data

# Set aside rightmost column (class labels)
Classe <- select(data, Classe) 
sep_data <- data[,-21]
SL_points <- sep_data

13) Pearson Dissimilarity

trans_sep_data <- as.data.frame(t(as.matrix(sep_data))) #  transpose
new_set <- cor(trans_sep_data) #  find correlations of transposed separated data
pearson_diss <- as.matrix(1- new_set) #  pearson dissimilarities
DistMatrix <- as.dist(pearson_diss) #  as distance matrix

14) Dissimilarity Matrix

For all the algorithms, including Single Linkage, We can see an improvement in how the clusters correspond approximately to the classes, where the two Leukemia sub-types are grouped more clearly.

Single Linkage seems to be less susceptible to noise in this case, and therefore could also be the reason as why it experiences less of a bridging affect.

Overall there are less scattered groupings, and with Ward’s algorithm already considered as the front runner out of algorithms tested, it has improved even more so. For this investigation, Ward’s algorithm, couple with the use of a Pearson dissimilarity matrix, appears to be the optimal strategy.

ACTIVITY 3: Clustering Genes (PART B)

15) Rescale Row-wise

data <- read.arff('yeast.arff') #  Data Set
Classe <- select(data, Classe) #  Separate Data
sep_data <- data[,-21] #  Separate 

rescaled <- sep_data/sqrt(sum(sep_data^2)) #  rescale row-wise with magnitude of 1
rescaled_by_row <- rescaled/max(rescaled)

16) Run HDBSCAN (with Euclidean distance)

hdbs <- hdbscan(rescaled_by_row , minPts = 5) #  hdbscan min = 5
plot(hdbs) #  plot result without class labels

hdbs$hc
